name: Nandita Iyer
text:
Interested in knowing about this¬†amazing journey from beehive to bottle? 
Watch this video made by @SaffolaHoney  
https://t.co/dqGVvuHQEq
[This thread was in collaboration with Saffola Honey]

name: Nandita Iyer
text: One reliable way to detect adulteration is an NMR (Nuclear Magnetic Resonance) test that will tell you if a particular brand of honey is 100% pure or not. All bottles of Saffola honey are tested with the NMR technique to ensure 100% purity. https://t.co/55ZtTHFFMD

name: Nandita Iyer
text:
Crystallisation is NOT an indication of impure honey. Honey in its natural state is a mix of supersaturated sugars which do tend to crystallize. Crystallized honey is perfectly good for consumption. Keep the bottle in warm
water or in the sun and it is ready to be used. https://t.co/EUZxA1UrvD

name: Nandita Iyer
text:
Given the sheer scale of effort it takes to produce it, honey is one of those products where adulteration is not only easy, it's extremely profitable. Sugar syrup produced from corn, rice or sugarcane are regularly used to defraud
customers. https://t.co/idAgrLV9H6

name: Nandita Iyer
text: Speaking of flowers, the flavour of honey depends on the variety of flowers the bees visit and extract nectar from. Eucalyptus honey will mildly remind you of toothpaste (because of the menthol in it) while buckwheat honey is darker and spicier. https://t.co/DNbq4YpFEK

name: Nandita Iyer
text: The queen bee is no lazy one. She lays 2500 eggs every day in summer. To put things in perspective, a hen lays less than 1 egg a day. The other bees fly up to 88,500 km and visit 2 million flowers to produce around half a kg of honey. https://t.co/Awf4BZzq3W

name: Nandita Iyer
text: This low moisture content and the acidic conditions created by gluconic acid is what gives honey its long shelf life and anti-bacterial properties. This is why it can be applied to wounds. But be careful when using wet spoons. Water & bacteria are good friends. https://t.co/H79Fpb80dr

name: Nandita Iyer
text:
Honey bees collectively fan their wings to cause water to evaporate from the nectar (which has 70% moisture) that they collect from flowers and turn it into honey
(which has 17% moisture). https://t.co/eL0AsMi3LU

name: Nandita Iyer
text:
A üßµ on honey and honey bees...

The most popular quote on honey bees is attributed to Einstein. The truth is he never said that and it is not even factually correct. But we cannot deny the fact that honey bees are critical in making us eat a diverse range of foods. https://t.co/JX8HgMibWL
